{"relationshipsSections":[{"title":"Inherits From","identifiers":["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Material"],"kind":"relationships","type":"inheritsFrom"},{"title":"Conforms To","identifiers":["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/GodotObject","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/s23CustomStringConvertibleP","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/SQ","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/SH","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/s12IdentifiableP","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/VariantRepresentable","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/VariantStorable"],"type":"conformsTo","kind":"relationships"}],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot"]]},"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial"},"schemaVersion":{"patch":0,"major":0,"minor":3},"kind":"symbol","primaryContentSections":[{"declarations":[{"tokens":[{"text":"class","kind":"keyword"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"text":"ProceduralSkyMaterial","kind":"identifier"}],"platforms":["macOS"],"languages":["swift"]}],"kind":"declarations"},{"kind":"content","content":[{"level":2,"anchor":"overview","type":"heading","text":"Overview"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" provides a way to create an effective background quickly by defining procedural parameters for the sun, the sky and the ground. The sky and ground are defined by a main color, a color at the horizon, and an easing curve to interpolate between them. Suns are described by a position in the sky, a color, and a max angle from the sun at which the easing curve ends. The max angle therefore defines the size of the sun in the sky."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" supports up to 4 suns, using the color, and energy, direction, and angular distance of the first four "},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/DirectionalLight3D","type":"reference"},{"text":" nodes in the scene. This means that the suns are defined individually by the properties of their corresponding ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/DirectionalLight3D","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"s and globally by "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/sunAngleMax","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial\/sunCurve"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ProceduralSkyMaterial"},{"type":"text","text":" uses a lightweight shader to draw the sky and is therefore suited for real time updates. This makes it a great option for a sky that is simple and computationally cheap, but unrealistic. If you need a more realistic procedural option, use "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PhysicalSkyMaterial","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":".","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}],"variants":[{"paths":["\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/proceduralskymaterial"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"abstract":[{"text":"A material that defines a simple sky for a ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Sky","type":"reference"},{"text":" resource.","type":"text"}],"metadata":{"roleHeading":"Class","modules":[{"name":"SwiftGodot"}],"externalID":"s:10SwiftGodot21ProceduralSkyMaterialC","role":"symbol","symbolKind":"class","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"ProceduralSkyMaterial","kind":"identifier"}],"title":"ProceduralSkyMateri